4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA REQUESTING AN INTERIM STUDY OF GUARDIANSHIP ISSUES; AND REQUIRING THAT THE
6 FINAL RESULTS OF THE STUDY BE REPORTED TO THE 70TH LEGISLATURE.
7
8 WHEREAS, Montana has established a system of guardianships and conservatorships to protect
9 people and their property when they cannot protect themselves; and
10 WHEREAS, court-appointed guardians and conservators are often untrained and lack experience to
11 perform their duties; and
12 WHEREAS, there have even been cases of experienced conservators committing acts of malfeasance;
13 and
14 WHEREAS, the system established in Montana to protect people who need protection is often not
15 protecting them; and
16 WHEREAS, Oregon has a Conservatorship Audit Program housed in the Attorney General's Office to
17 assist courts to understand and assess guardianship and conservatorship case filings; and
18 WHEREAS, in 2011, Minnesota established a Conservator Account Auditing Program in the Judicial
19 Branch to improve conservatorship oversight and reduce administrative costs; and
20 WHEREAS, several states provide licensing or certification and training of guardians and conservators.
21
22 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF
23 THE STATE OF MONTANA:
24 That the Legislative Council be requested to designate an appropriate interim committee or statutory
25 committee, pursuant to section 5-5-217, MCA, to study guardianship issues in Montana, including but not
26 limited to training, licensing, certification, and auditing of guardians and conservators.
27 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the study:
28 (1) review existing resources in Montana for guardians and conservators;
