1 (2) examine programs other states use to train, license, certify, and audit guardians and
2 conservators;
3 (3) identify potential costs of programs and funding sources;
4 (4) determine where a Montana program should be placed for administrative purposes; and
5 (5) involve input and feedback from stakeholders, including but not limited to guardians,
6 conservators, family members of those needing assistance, organizations involved in supporting guardians and
7 incapacitated individuals, judges, staff from the Department of Public Health and Human Services and the
8 Department of Justice, and any other stakeholders considered relevant by the committee.
9 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that all aspects of the study, including presentation and review
10 requirements, be concluded prior to September 15, 2026.
11 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the final results of the study, including any findings, conclusions,
12 comments or recommendations of the appropriate committee, be reported to the 69th Legislature.
